This is a lever extension for the Printrbot Metal Plus, single-extruder model 1412. This is for the Version 1 extruder, not Version 2. It's roughly based on the design for the Printrbot Simple lever by SlovenskaPosta. The Metal Plus has limited space between the print head lever and the side z-axis rods. It also has a hex bolt-head between the extruder motor and the existing lever, so I had to recreate the 3D model with the sizes adjusted. I also included more brace material under the finger pressure point, since printing this object vertically could lead to de-lamination of the end of the lever without the extra. It would also be best to print at 100% infill, to maximize the amount of plastic and strengthen the piece.

It should print without any support material. I was able to print several design iterations without issue. The tops of the holes might have slight drooping based on your printer's ability to bridge small gaps, but it should be minimal and can be cleared out with a knife blade or blunt object to push through.

To install, remove the tension screw and spring from the existing lever, then slide the printed piece over top. Push it tight against the right end of the lever so that the holes line back up with those in the metal. Re-insert the spring and tension screw and tighten back to the amount needed for your filament.

The model was created in the free version of 123D Design. I've included the model file for anyone that would like to make modifications.

description.text:
This is a memory coin for my son, with his face on one side and "DADDY LOVES YOU" on the other.

This is a highly detailed project.  I've attempted to build this design TWICE, with different scales and different settings, and both with success at first but failure before 1/4-way through the print process.
Good luck... see what you can do with it!  I generally use CAD for architectural things, since I'm a home builder (general contractor) and insurance adjuster.  I don't have much experience with complex curves.  Otherwise, I have about 100 really cool car designs (drawings, mostly... some CAD) that I would LOVE to post here!

UGHHH!

Please use these "thing" files as examples only.  Print it if you wish, but please keep in mind that my son's face is on one side of this coin.  (No, you pedophiles will not be able to recognize him by this 3D file or even the highest-quality print of this file.
Given that my wife will most certainly take custody of my son after the divorce, I wanted my son to have a trinket of some sort that means something to him.  My son loves money, and loves counting it.  I'd hope that he would count this coin as the most valuable one in his inventory.

title: Filter Ring for DJI Phantom 3 and CollegeGeezer's Die Cut ND Filters
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I am providing these rings here for your personal use only.
You MAY print as many as you need for your own use.
You may NOT make these to sell/trade/barter (either the printed part nor the model files).
You may NOT make derivative objects from these models for any reason.

This is a filter holder ring set that fits the DJI Phantom 3 line of quadcopters (drones). Its designed to hold the ND and CP filter set tht College Geezer is selling here:
http://www.phantompilots.com/threads/professionally-die-cut-nd-filters-only-2-each.67832/

There are two STL files. You only need one. I provided a second one (the one with 16 fingers, NDFilterRing2) that has a looser fit in case anyone wanted it. The one with only 8 fingers (NDFilterRing) is the one I personally use on my P3P and P3A birds and is the one I recommend you print and use.

These rings are designed to hold the larger filter size that CG is selling now. However, there is a small inset in the bezel of both rings that will accept the smaller set he used to sell (now discontinued) in case you have that set.

These are intended to slide over the stock UV filter DJI supplied with your Phantom.

After print, the weight of both rings should be just under 2g (in abs).

NOTE: Yes, the fingers are tapered. They are thicker at the end than they are at the base. This is by design.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 5

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.15mm layer height

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Print with 10+ outer layers and 10+ top/bottom layers to force a 100% perimeter print with no infill (which you want for the base and fingers).

You want the small layer height to get proper dimensions on the inset ring on the bezel for use with the smaller filters. If you do not have the smaller filters and don't plan to have any, then you can up the layer height to whatever you are comfortable with (.20mm or .30mm).

No supports are needed. No raft is needed (at least I needed none).

I would recommend NOT sanding or finishing these. The roughness of the fingers adds to its grip on the Phantom's camera filter ring to hold it in place. If you were to sand them or acetone smooth them, you might loose some of that grip. However, I have not had one fall off in flight yet.

The design includes a socket for an M3 screw that you can use to affix the the fan and stepper wires to. STL came out with the model on its side, but of course you'll want to print it flat.

This is a design I made based on the Glass Sword from Skyrim. I designed it using 123d Design.

description.text:
This is my personal remix of two things I wanted to add to my WDi3. Putting both those things at the same time on my printer would have been a little overloading. That's why I decided to combine them. I also added my little touch by adding a ball joint to the lock-nut located inside the front feet. I added a support arm on the back brace to keep the heated bed wires from getting tangled on the Y-Axis bed, specially when the Y-Axis is at its YLarge Limit.

I got the Level Foot from my local hardware store. I think Mal3D got his at Home Depot. These are cheap and allow you to level your printer on uneven surface. On my setup, I used lock-nut at all 8 points, just to make sure vibration wouldn't loosen up standard nuts.

title: G2S 3-Bearing Carriage
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a new carriage for the Geeetech Delta G2S printer. It features a third linear bearing for greatly improved lateral stability, compared to the stock two-bearing carriage. Spacing between the diagonal rods matches the original, but mounted as high and close to the vertical rods as possible. You will need to adjust dimensions in your firmware after mounting this carriage.

The Carriage Base is a fairly large and complex piece, but it can tolerate a surprising amount of warping at the corners and still produce a perfectly serviceable unit. Almost all of the critical alignment is designed into structures away from corner warp zones.

Because these bearing covers are slightly taller than the originals, I needed to extend the length of my Servo Carriage Latch slightly. The updated version has been included.

You will need to build a full set of three carriages. One carriage consists of:
1 Carriage Base
1 Carriage Belt Block
1 Carriage Belt Clamp
3 Carriage Bearing Covers
3 LM10UU linear bearings
10 M3 lock nuts (nylon insert)
9 M3x12mm cap screws
1 m3 washer (for belt clamp screw)
1 M3x40mm endstop screw (You can reuse ones from original carriages, springs not needed.)

Fully assembled, as shown, it weighs in at 131 grams, compared to 244g for the original metal carriage. The 3 linear bearings account for more than half of of its mass (72g).

You can see the carriages in action here.

UPDATE: Beefed up the middle post a bit. I broke one (doing something stupid). It broke more easily than I felt it should have, so I've made it a little heavier.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I've got a small fleet of 7 Rep2's and I have a few gripes regarding the current cooling fan mount, which this design addresses:

  • The overhang gets in the way when, due to major clogs/gripping filament stuck inside the extruder, I must get under the extruder motor to trim material away from it. - The overhang here is easily removeable, but securly attached.

  • The mounting screws that attach the mount to the aluminum block are all but inaccessible inside the cable cavity. If the mount ever needs to be removed, it takes nearly ten minutes of making 1/8 turns repeatedly with the allen wrench to get the two screws off and takes just as much time to get them on. - Two holes in the top of part 2 of this assembly make it easy to get allen wrenches with a clear axis of rotation down to the screws.

  • The entire mount easily bends when the block is warm and is almost impossible to get back into the correct shape thanks to those two mounting screws being attached via a less than 1mm plastic plate to the rest of the assembly. - The new attachment plate has been thickened slightly and also axially reinforced. It's proven very difficult to bend, even when the block is above typical extrusion temps.

  • The cable cavity is aggravatingly small in an attempt to provide as much space as possible for the head to move along the X-axis. Unfortunately, MBI overshot this limitation by about 5mm at the cost of easy head reassembly. - I expanded the depth of the cable cavity by about 2mm, still maintaining a wide berth for the head to move to the -X extreme. Things now fit much more easily, and accessing/reassembling the driveblock and extruder has become much faster.

  • The heating element cable has no direct access to the head via the cable cavity, requiring it to uselessly loop through the cable cavity and take up even more space than necessary. - A chase for the cable runs from the cavity down to the head itself, making for tidy cable management and opening up more space in the cavity.

Used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:64669 as a basic template, then cleaned up some of the dimensions. Got the idea for a cable chase from this design, though the top holes for accessing the mounting screws was a matter of co-evolution. Thanks bluejay117!

title: Makerfarm i3v - MB Plus HotEnd mount.

description.text:
I purchased an MB Plus hotend (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:637748) as I tragically broke my E3DV6 and wanted to try something new. Since I could not get it mounted to my X carriage and couldn't find any designs to get this mounted on my printer, I had to come up with my own design.

I made two designs, one has arms that go into the X backplate and one without the arms and instead M3 nut and bolt slots so you can use the original wooden arms. The design with the arms will print just fine with supports added.

I've also included the SolidWorks part files. I am using a direct drive extruder made by someone over at YouMagine.com, but the original extruder (Wades) that came with the i3v SHOULD work with this design with no issues.

The hotend requires a 5mm mounting plate, the one I have came with the printer but if you purchased yours with an E3D hotend then it would have came with a 6mm plate. You could either buy the plate or print one, I'm sure there are some designs out there.

I will probably improve on the design in the future, but for now it works great.

I'm all over the place today, so I may have forgotten to mention any details. If you need any help please ask away in the comments.

Update: Version 2 of the plate with arms now available. I went back to the Wades extruder and the hotend was sagging way too much so I had to go back into SolidWorks and work on a new design. It much better now with 0 sag whatsoever.

Tennis fans will appreciate this... print one for yourself or as a small fun gift. The racquet has been directly scaled rom a current top level tennis racquet. Even if you're not a tennis fan this quick print is fun to try... see how well your machine prints the fine strings.

To make your recessed print multi-coloured. with a 1mm raft, pause your machine at 35% and 85% to switch in / out colours. Easy to do and the result is great.

description.text:
Hi,
now GEEETech proposes the Acrylic Prusa I3 pro series, B for single extruder and C for dual extruder, with metallic parts instead of original printer ones.
Quite immediately I’ve ordered the upgrade kit in order to improve the stability and the quality of my, already not-so-bad printer, unfortunately the customization I’ve designed for the plastic version of this printer cannot be used on the metal one, so I’ve started designing a completely new customization, starting with all lesson learned from my original customization!
One of the infinites lesson learned from my original customization was the position of LCD panel.
With original GEEETech Top Mount position any action on rotary encoder can introduce a little noise on frame stability and this is not really good!
So I’ve chose, for my new customization, to move the LCD bottom ahead of front acrylic plate in order to avoid any vibration/movement of frame in case of action over rotary encoder!
In same box I’ve also moved the main power contact, that was complex to operate on my desk due to position where I normally take the printer, and together to LCD is really nice!
I’ve also decide to put a wood basement under my printer, in order to keep printer locked and avoid any frame movement during printer displacement, so I primary designed my new LCD Box to be screwed on this wood!
In this new LCD Box you can found:

1) All component of LCD Box, with also Power switch and LED control
2) Optional component for people do not have wood where screw all
3) The protection for cables, with complex component in multiple version:
a. Normal, that need support to be printer:
b. In 4 version, that can be printer without any support and blend to final form

As usual in all my design I’ve split all in order to have an easy print of each, and also an easy mounting after print!

IF YOU “FALL IN LOVE” OF THIS DESIGN, PLEASE, REMEMBER THAT IT TAKE TIME TO BE CREATED, DESIGNED AND SHARED… SO “MAYBE” YOU CAN USE THE “TIP DESIGNED” BUTTON ON MY PROFILE!

description.text:
I highly recommend using the further improved design at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18657, that jonaskuehling uploaded recently Prusa Mendel x carriage using 4 lm8uu linear bearings in screw-fastened holders for easy (dis-)assembly. No zipties, no fragile and imprecise snap-in-brackets. I didn't like the snap-fit bearing holders in Greg Frosts's x carriage for the same reason why jonaskuehling made the slim LM8UU holder derivate. So I modified Greg's carriage and integrated the new bearing holders for an easy-to-disassemble x carriage. I attached the OpenSCAD files including Greg's configuration for some variables and Jonas' lm8uu-holder. I tidied up the source code a bit, but there are still some unnecessary lines left over from greg's code. The code is not overly clean and parametric due to the lack of time. UPDATE 31.01.2012
  • Reattached Greg's fan mount to the carriage. I updated the OpenSCAD file and added another STL.
    • UPDATE 03.02.2012
  • One linear bearing could not slide into its bracket since the fan mount was blocking the path. I cut away a little clearance.
    Not the smartest solution, but quick and functional.

Slide in 4 LM8UU linear bearings.
Gently secure the bearings with 4 M3x20 screws and 4 M3 nuts.

description.text: Few ages ago I was using a piece of paper "quite a 2D thing" to get 3 dimensional models, so this is a tribute to a couple of my first ever "made things". It's a quick OpenSCAD that don't take in account some important aspects to make the models easyly printable. Take a look to the instructions and the scad script itself for more info. Some more pictures: http://www.flickr.com/photos/aubenc/sets/72157628926382411/

Because I cheat with the dimensions and thickness of the walls and because the OpenSCAD is not making any adjustment, it may be difficult to find out what wall thickness you need. The models I provide are the ones that bot1334 got to print. However, bot1334 is a cupcake, DC motor extruder, home made hot end... pffff. There's a zip file conatining a bunch of stl with different sizes for the walls. Hopefully you'll find one that works for you, otherwise... Do take a look to the OpenSCAD (non OpenSCAD users too), there is more explanations and you can use it to set the walls to something thick: 2mm? 20mm? 50mm?? why not! The zip contains the models with walls from 0.75mm to 1.15mm in 0.05mm increments. For the bird, you'll find it with and without design-support. The support version here, has a gap of 0.50mm between model and support, that's fine for oozing printers like mine. There are other models ready with other gap parameter vallues in the zip (0.15mm, 0.20mm and 0.25 if I'm not wrong). May be, the best is to take a look to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16146 and just use a bird without design-support ;-) One version of the boat has a little more of detail than the other, you choose... If instead of one thin wall you get 2 thinner walls, choose a model from the zip with thinner walls. If ReplicatorG complains about "end points I-don't-know-what", choose another model from the zip with thicker walls. You do not want blobs in the walls! Choose the right wall thickness stl !! Do check the sliced model (Skeinview/iso / things 6236, 12518, 14980 / your preferred slicer own's viewer). Walls thick enough to avoid slicer issues but still too thin may end up with some layers missing!! The bird... well it's a bird so it's only thinking in taking off from the build platform, do your best to see that it waits until print completion (I used blue painters tape) Skeinforge standard did a better job than Skeinforge 35 (normally it's the opposite) For the curious: Diameter of filament out of bot1334 nozzle is 0.61 mm, all skeinforge parameters set to default for Cupcake HBP profile but: Flowrate set to 215, Feedrate and Travel Feedrate set to 26mm/s, Layer Height set to 0.34. It took 1h03min for the bird and 21min for the boat. .....

description.text: Pawprint coin

This iPad holder supports the iPad 2 & 3. It can be adjusted for the optimal viewing angle by sliding the adjustable drive at the front of the holder. A little bit of grease will help move the drive gear; it needs to fit tight, so wear it in a little after printing. The "balancer" is to hold the cable. The balancer should be glued into the cover. The pin should be cut down to fit the little holders. Alternatively, a paper clip can be used.

This is version 3 of the holder, but the first version to be published on Thingiverse.
  • Print all the parts. Print the drive gear top down.
  • Insert the drive gear into the collar in the base and twist for a few minutes until the movement is smooth. Remove the drive gear and repeat with the riser.
  • Apply a little grease to the drive gear collar and riser screw. Fit them together and put them into their appropriate holders. Rotate the gear until the screw is as far down as it can go, then back it off a little so that it isn't frozen in the holder.
  • Put the cover on, using either the pin or a paper clip (cut to size) to mate the cover to the base.
  • Glue the balancer into the cover.
  • Slide a cable into the holder. You can glue it in if you wish. Now the holder is good to go!

description.text:
version 1:
Kids FooGo thermos lid cracked from a thermos bought back in 2010. I designed a replacement part that functions as the original. It seals the straw and the pressure hole and stays latched. Might not fit the new thermos designs.I printed several version to make the latch work properly. I printed it top side down. The top has a 6 degree slope so you can set your CAM software properly to make it flat.

Version 2:
So I had to make a version 2. The fit of the original was acceptable but not as good as I would have liked. So I messed with the latch and made it tighter and slightly stronger. I just had to tweak it and really like the new fit.

version 3:
So I found that some of the straws leak when in use and then found my air hole block was in the wrong location. It has been fixed in version 3 now and all seems well with 2 different straws.

Final Update:
So I have all the kinks worked out. I did find that I had to use an XActo knife and trim a little bit of the edge off of the latch part on the lid. It prevents the button from coming all the way out when the lid is closed. It is just a little bit off the end of the triangle that locks into the receiver of the button latching the lid closed.

Update: October 17, 2016
I just uploaded the button that corresponds to these FooGo lids. It is at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1833663 on thingiverse.

This is a fictional landscape model (15cm x 15 cm) which should help pupils better to understand topographic maps. Exercises for using these models in geography or science lessons are available here* or in Kristjan Rea master's thesis “Applying virtual 3D-models and physical 3D-models created by a 3D-printer for learning about the topic “Landforms and Groups of Landforms” in basic schools”. Link for the master's thesis: https://goo.gl/3Aq2gR
NB! It is recommended that pupils themselves participate in the process of making the landscape model.

See on väljamõeldud maastikumudel (15cm x 15 cm), mis peaks aitama õpilastel paremini mõista topograafilisi kaarte. Ülesande, kuidas seda mudelit geograafia või loodusõpetuse tundides rakendada leiate Kristjan Rea magistritööst “Virtuaalsete 3D-mudelite ja 3D-printeriga loodud füüsiliste mudelite rakendamine „Pinnavormide ja pinnamoe“ teema õppimiseks põhikoolis”. Veebilink magistritööle: https://goo.gl/3Aq2gR
NB! Võimalusel võiksid õpilased osaleda ka maastikumudeli valmistamisprotessis (modelleerimises jne).

Step 1

In Adobe Illustrator CS6 the top view of the landscape model (incl. contour lines) was made.

Adobe Illustrator CS6'ga joonistati maastikumudeli ülaltvaade (sh horisontaalid).

Step 2

Illustrator file was modelled in Blender 2.76 and then converted into STL file.

Illustratoris loodud faili modelleeriti Blender 2.76's ning valmis mudel konverteeriti STL vormingusse.

Step 3

After printing the model paths (green), river (blue) and exercise points (black) were drawn by marker.

Pärast mudeli printimist joonistati sellele markeriga rajad (roheline), jõgi (sinine) ja ülesande punktid (mustad).

NB!

For printing this kind of a model it is recommended to use printer that has heated bed.

Sellise mudeli printimiseks on soovitatav kasutada printerit, millel on soojendusega alus.

description.header: *How to use this model in classroom
description.text:
Exercise for this landscape model

Inspect landscape model and answer the following questions. Write the correct letter from landscape model on the dotted line or underline the right answer.

1) The highest point of the landscape model is located on the point ...
2) When moving from the point I to point E the altitude decreases/stays the same/increases.
3) From point G it is possible to see point I. Yes/No. Explain shortly!
4) Compare two slopes. Slope on the northeast side is steeper than/equally steep/less steeper than slope on the northwest side of the landscape model.
5) Point B is located higher/almost at the same height as/lower than point J.
6) River flows from west to south/south to west.
7) Point H is located at top of the hill/on the slope of the hill/in the valley.
8) The lowest point of the landscape model is located on the point ...
9) Point A is located lower than/almost at the same height as/higher than point H.
10) The steepest slope is located on the northeast/southeast/southwest side of the landscape model.
11) From point F it is possible to see point D. Yes/No. Explain shortly!
12) When moving from the point D to point C the altitude decreases/stays the same/increases.
13) Point M is located at top of the hill/on the slope of the hill/in the valley.
